It's clearer that an empty dict is returned.

You forgot to handle the non-JSON case.  How about this?

```
from requests.compat import json

try:
    error = res.json()
except json.JSONDecodeError:
    error = {'message': 'The API did not respond with JSON, but: "{0}"'.format(res.text[:1000])', "error_code": "InvalidResponseFormat"}
```

This will likely mess up any enzyme tests for `Cell`. The reason is that this actually returns a wrapper around Cell so that now it looks like this: `<ContextMenuLayer><Cell /></ContextMenuLayer>`. For your tests the best way to do it is to export the cell class above and then import that.
```
export class Cell extends React.Component { ... }
export default contextMenuLayer(...)(Cell);
```
Then in your test you would import it with the braces.
```
import { Cell } from '../../../../src/notebook/components/cell/cell';
```

@hackaugusto 

it works like this

```
import structlog

log = structlog.get_logger()
def f(): g()
try:
    f()
except Exception as e:
    log.error('HALP', e=e, exc_info=True)
```

Of course it might be possible to configure `structlog` to include traceback automatically for `exception` log level.

@alykhantejani I actually did that due to a weird behaviour of `np.random` which makes all the workers produce the same random numbers, so each mini-batch ended up being identical when run in parallel. 

More here:
https://discuss.pytorch.org/t/why-does-numpy-random-rand-produce-the-same-values-in-different-cores/12005

